text: Jimmy Wong played a  Silas+Sidar on GameKnights and it's something I want to try to brew eventually because it blew my mind when I first saw it
That sounds pretty cool <@U3FV90TCZ>, I haven't seen that episode yet.

I'll also say that I get why they were all so generically designed. It's really the only way to build them to encourage the most mix/match combos. It completely makes sense. But the end result winds up being 99% of people building the decks just pair generically strong partner x with generically strong partner y and throw in a bunch of generically strong shit.

What I personally would have preferred for partners was specific pairings, i.e. a white/red Gerrard specifically designed and only allowed to pair with a blue/green Hanna or something, that way the deck could be built for a specific purpose and you don't encourage min-maxing the way they do now. That's probably way less interesting to people not me though, so I get why they didn't go that route.

Technically partners opens up way more than that in terms of possibilities so I get what he meant by it, but it's a different kind of open ended, an open ended to the point where there's no form if that makes sense.

A kid fingerpainting random smears is way more free than someone trying to paint a still life, but the restriction of choosing a subject and making it work is way more interesting to me than the freedom the fingerpainting provides.

Has anyone else seen this particular cycle: new edh player builds a kind of thematic deck, we'll say Alesha ETB stuff because that's the most recent example I've seen. He loses more than he wins for various reasons, but mostly the losses seem to come from play style/unfamiliarity with multiplayer differences compared to single player (too aggressive and/or overextends, can't read politics, can't assess multiplayer threat, etc.). As a result he decides to "improve" his deck by picking up "good" cards, maybe a Sheoldred or a Liliana of the Veil. Unfortunately while those cards are technically "better" than the Mogg War Marshal he was running, it's not necessarily better in that particular deck as it interacts with what the deck was trying to do way less. As a result, the original problems still exist, and in "strenghtening" his deck he has wound up actually weakening it, so there aren't any added wins. The solution? "Improve" the deck by picking up more "good" cards, Rinse and repeat until the original effective deck is just a mess of ten dollar cards that don't work together at all.
It's not something that happens all the time, but I've seen it more than once. Just wondering if anyone else has observed that.
You're in technology <@U4V5EHQ2G>. This is solving the problem by throwing hardware at it.
Hah! An it's probably not a coincidence that it's almost always tech people I see doing that
You don't make the process more efficient, you make the inefficiency irrelevant.
that's how my second deck ever went, trostani
it did great things a few times, but I didn't know how to play it
and then I "tuned" it until it fell out of what it did best
and then I took it apart

It's a common trap for EDH players, and even extends into normal magic. You can upgrade a car or a network to make it perform as good as you like but the operator has to have the skill to get the full potential out of the hardware.

I think it's hard for users in this scenario to identify the disparity in skill because they are too close. Looking in the mirror and becoming more critical of your ability to use the system is at the bottom of the list. It's easier and feels more natural for them to start altering the system to provide a level of comfort in feeling that the system is as good as it can be.
In this case, a deck. They feel momentary comfort that Sheoldred lurks in the 99 until the same play choices are made and the losses continue to rack up.
Someone should write an article on how to identify and avoid that process.
Someone involved in tech, perhaps?

text: Sandbagging and Alt win cons are the only way I ever win

I think this all boils down to a skill of the game that you can't really teach but have to learn over time, and that's proper timing of spells. The new Commander player is not going to know how to do it well since it's very different from 1v1, and it's still difficult even for players with years of experience. I know I'm not perfect at it, but it sure is great when you make a brilliant series of plays to either win or stay in the game. I'm talking about things like baiting counters or board wipes, catching players with well timed removal or destrying other players' expectations on what you and/or your deck can do.
